Head lice, systemic manifestations: RFI 980418193509
[1
Date: Mon, 20 Apr 1998 15:01:56 -0400
From: Eric James, Ph.D.
Via: Cynthia Karr <karrc@smtpgw2.musc.edu>

The following is a response obtained from Eric James, PhD, Medical
University of South Carolina, in answer to Michae Fraze's request for
information.
The symptoms mentioned in this case are all characteristic of long-term
head lice infestations. Hirschfelder (1919) was probably the first to
report a rise in body temperature (fever, sometimes leading to a febrile
condition), generalized diffuse allergic rash, headache, heaviness of the
limbs, stiffness of the muscles and general
lassitude. Adenopathy is common, principally of the cervical lymph nodes in
cases of head lice (many references). Contact reactions (e.g. edema) may
also occur in some patients anywhere on the body as a result of exposure to
louse feces. These symptoms seem to result directly from actively feeding
lice (e.g. saliva, feces) and after the lice have been removed the symptoms
subside. Secondary infection also may occur: exudative crusting, pyoderma
and impetigo, though usually limited to the scalp. It is claimed that lice
are the commonest cause of impetigo in developing countries (Taplin and
Meinking, 1988).
--
Eric James, PhD,
Medical University of South Carolina
