[5
Date: Mon, 20 Apr 1998 17:21:01 +0000
From: Bruce Harrison <BRUCE_HARRISON@WSRO.ENR.State.NC.US>

Michael, you should probably have your niece checked for Trench Fever (or
Quintana Fever), a louse-borne bacterial infection caused by _Bartonella
quintana_. I am unable to identify where your niece lives, which would help
in the identification of a possible pathogen. However, the cyclic nature and
signs and symptoms are quite similar to Trench Fever, a nonfatal bacterial
infection that varies in severity.
Another likely sounding possibility, which does not involve lice, but does
involve fleas and pet house cats, is Cat Scratch Disease (CSD), another
bacterial disease caused by _Bartonella henselae_, and another similar CSD
disease caused by a newly described pathogen, _Bartonella clarridgeiae_. If
your niece has a cat, particularly kittens, or pets kittens, this would be
my bet.
--
Bruce A. Harrison <bruce_harrison@wsro.enr.state.nc.us>
